<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="33" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,1090,220,1587]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,519,283,307]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
Description. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[256,339,283,307]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Female</emphasis>
(
<emphasis bold="true" box="[353,504,284,307]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">macropterous</emphasis>
).
</emphasis>
Body pale yellowish; antennal segments III–V shaded at margins, IV–V brownish yellow distally, VI–IX yellowish brown (
<figureCitation box="[846,910,316,339]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1516,1535]" captionTargetBox="[212,1066,219,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[212,1066,219,1497]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Eremiothrips eshghii sp. nov. 1–6 – female: 1 – head and pronotum; 2 – mesonotum and metanotum; 3 – meso- and metasternum; 4 – tergites VIII–X; 5 – antenna; 6 – antennal segments V–IX. 7–8 – male: 7 – sternites IV–VII; 8 – tergite IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4503841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4503841/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); pronotum with dark spot in the middle, setae on head pale, other setae light brown; fore wing including clavus uniformly pale. Head broader than long (
<figureCitation box="[592,654,380,403]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1516,1535]" captionTargetBox="[212,1066,219,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[212,1066,219,1497]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Eremiothrips eshghii sp. nov. 1–6 – female: 1 – head and pronotum; 2 – mesonotum and metanotum; 3 – meso- and metasternum; 4 – tergites VIII–X; 5 – antenna; 6 – antennal segments V–IX. 7–8 – male: 7 – sternites IV–VII; 8 – tergite IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4503841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4503841/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), slightly overhanging antennal segment I, compound eyes with 6 pigmented facets ventrally, arranged in 3 rows; 3 pairs of ocellar setae present, pair III in front of hind ocelli within triangle, about as long as ocellar setae I and II; 4–5 pairs of postocular setae, all setae on head short; maxillary palps 3-segmented. Antennae 9-segmented (
<figureCitation box="[370,433,508,531]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1516,1535]" captionTargetBox="[212,1066,219,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[212,1066,219,1497]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Eremiothrips eshghii sp. nov. 1–6 – female: 1 – head and pronotum; 2 – mesonotum and metanotum; 3 – meso- and metasternum; 4 – tergites VIII–X; 5 – antenna; 6 – antennal segments V–IX. 7–8 – male: 7 – sternites IV–VII; 8 – tergite IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4503841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4503841/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
), segment I without median dorsal apical setae, III and IV with weak microtrichia and forked sensoria; segment V with inner sensorium conspicuous, longer than apical width of segment, VI without pedicel (
<figureCitation box="[649,715,572,595]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1516,1535]" captionTargetBox="[212,1066,219,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[212,1066,219,1497]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Eremiothrips eshghii sp. nov. 1–6 – female: 1 – head and pronotum; 2 – mesonotum and metanotum; 3 – meso- and metasternum; 4 – tergites VIII–X; 5 – antenna; 6 – antennal segments V–IX. 7–8 – male: 7 – sternites IV–VII; 8 – tergite IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4503841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4503841/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,1090,220,1587]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
Pronotum weakly transversely striate, with no long setae (
<figureCitation box="[769,831,604,627]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1516,1535]" captionTargetBox="[212,1066,219,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[212,1066,219,1497]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Eremiothrips eshghii sp. nov. 1–6 – female: 1 – head and pronotum; 2 – mesonotum and metanotum; 3 – meso- and metasternum; 4 – tergites VIII–X; 5 – antenna; 6 – antennal segments V–IX. 7–8 – male: 7 – sternites IV–VII; 8 – tergite IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4503841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4503841/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) (sometimes with inner pair of posteroangular setae longer than remaining setae, about 14 microns), about 30 discal setae present; anterior margin with 3–4 pairs of setae, posterior margin with 4 pairs of setae scarcely longer than discal setae, basantra membranous, without setae, ferna divided into two halves, not connected. Mesonotum with transverse lines, campaniform sensilla inconspicuous (
<figureCitation box="[121,189,764,787]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1516,1535]" captionTargetBox="[212,1066,219,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[212,1066,219,1497]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Eremiothrips eshghii sp. nov. 1–6 – female: 1 – head and pronotum; 2 – mesonotum and metanotum; 3 – meso- and metasternum; 4 – tergites VIII–X; 5 – antenna; 6 – antennal segments V–IX. 7–8 – male: 7 – sternites IV–VII; 8 – tergite IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4503841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4503841/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Mesosternal anterior margin with about 10 setae; mesoacrotergite with 4 pairs of microsetae. Metanotal sculpture longitudinally linear on anterior half, median setae well behind anterior margin; campaniform sensilla absent (
<figureCitation box="[706,775,828,851]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1516,1535]" captionTargetBox="[212,1066,219,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[212,1066,219,1497]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Eremiothrips eshghii sp. nov. 1–6 – female: 1 – head and pronotum; 2 – mesonotum and metanotum; 3 – meso- and metasternum; 4 – tergites VIII–X; 5 – antenna; 6 – antennal segments V–IX. 7–8 – male: 7 – sternites IV–VII; 8 – tergite IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4503841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4503841/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); mesothoracic sternopleural suture present; spinula present on mesosternum, absent on metasternum (
<figureCitation box="[881,945,860,883]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1516,1535]" captionTargetBox="[212,1066,219,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[212,1066,219,1497]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Eremiothrips eshghii sp. nov. 1–6 – female: 1 – head and pronotum; 2 – mesonotum and metanotum; 3 – meso- and metasternum; 4 – tergites VIII–X; 5 – antenna; 6 – antennal segments V–IX. 7–8 – male: 7 – sternites IV–VII; 8 – tergite IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4503841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4503841/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Tarsi 2-segmented. Fore wing slender with posterior cilia wavy; first vein with 7–9 setae on basal half and 3 widely spaced setae on distal half, second vein with 8–9 widely spaced setae; clavus with 4–5 veinal and 1 discal seta.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,1090,220,1587]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
Abdominal tergites weakly sculptured medially, without ctenidia or craspeda; tergite II without lateral marginal setae; tergal campaniform sensilla posterolateral to median setae, near posterior margin; posteromarginal comb on VIII complete, surface with faint transverse reticulation, median campaniform sensilla situated between S1 seta and posterior margin, closer to the posterior margin; tergite VIII setae S1 a little longer than setae S2, tergite IX median dorsal setae not extending to posterior margin of tergite, and with two pairs of campaniform sensilla near the margin, setae S2 slightly longer than S1 (
<figureCitation box="[731,796,1180,1203]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1516,1535]" captionTargetBox="[212,1066,219,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[212,1066,219,1497]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Eremiothrips eshghii sp. nov. 1–6 – female: 1 – head and pronotum; 2 – mesonotum and metanotum; 3 – meso- and metasternum; 4 – tergites VIII–X; 5 – antenna; 6 – antennal segments V–IX. 7–8 – male: 7 – sternites IV–VII; 8 – tergite IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4503841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4503841/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); tergite X with dorsal split short; ovipositor developed. Sternites without discal setae or marginal craspedum, II with 2 pairs of marginal setae, III–VII with 3 pairs; pleurotergites with no discal setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,1090,220,1587]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis box="[144,298,1276,1299]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Measurements</emphasis>
(
<typeStatus box="[310,405,1276,1299]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">holotype</typeStatus>
female, in µm). Body length 1273. Head length 100; width across eyes 138. Pronotum, length 113; maximum width 172. Fore wing length 574. Metanotal median setae 20. Tergite VIII setae 
<geoCoordinate box="[409,474,1340,1363]" degrees="1" direction="south" minutes="28" orientation="latitude" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" precision="925" value="-1.4666667">S1 28</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[486,550,1340,1363]" degrees="2" direction="south" minutes="21" orientation="latitude" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" precision="925" value="-2.35">S2 21</geoCoordinate>
; tergite IX setae 
<geoCoordinate box="[734,798,1340,1363]" degrees="1" direction="south" minutes="52" orientation="latitude" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" precision="925" value="-1.8666667">S1 52</geoCoordinate>
, S2 63. Antennal segments III–IX length: 32, 31, 31, 35, 12, 11, 17.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,1090,220,1587]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[144,383,1403,1427]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Male (macropterous).</emphasis>
Similar to female in colour and structure but smaller, with transverse pore plate on discal area of sternites IV–VII (
<figureCitation box="[665,730,1436,1459]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1516,1535]" captionTargetBox="[212,1066,219,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[212,1066,219,1497]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Eremiothrips eshghii sp. nov. 1–6 – female: 1 – head and pronotum; 2 – mesonotum and metanotum; 3 – meso- and metasternum; 4 – tergites VIII–X; 5 – antenna; 6 – antennal segments V–IX. 7–8 – male: 7 – sternites IV–VII; 8 – tergite IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4503841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4503841/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
); abdominal tergum VIII without comb on posterior margin, IX at posterior margin with two long, biserially toothed processes (
<figureCitation box="[121,186,1500,1523]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1516,1535]" captionTargetBox="[212,1066,219,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[212,1066,219,1497]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Eremiothrips eshghii sp. nov. 1–6 – female: 1 – head and pronotum; 2 – mesonotum and metanotum; 3 – meso- and metasternum; 4 – tergites VIII–X; 5 – antenna; 6 – antennal segments V–IX. 7–8 – male: 7 – sternites IV–VII; 8 – tergite IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4503841" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4503841/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
